citations.narrative:
It was observed that the public may be able to make contact with several animals while they were in their primary
enclosures due to absent barrier measures.
The varied height vertical log wall of the African Crested Porcupine enclosure measures 23 to 36 inches tall on the public
facing side, allowing the public to reach over the enclosure wall and make contact with the animals. An approximately foot
wide depression in the ground is present at the wall base on the animal side of the enclosure, which measures
approximately 45 inches from ground to top of tallest log. There are some gaps between the logs that allow the public to
stick a hand through.
A section of the wall of the primary enclosure containing 2 Crested Screamers consists entirely of chain link fencing
measuring 59 inches tall. There is no public barrier at this section of the fence that prevents the public from having contact
with the animals.
The varied height vertical log wall of the 1 Crested Screamer enclosure measures 14 to 43 inches tall on the public facing
side, allowing the public to reach over or step over the enclosure wall and make contact with the animal. There are some
gaps between the logs that allow the public to stick a hand through.
Failure to provide sufficient distance and/or barriers between the animal and the viewing public may pose a risk of harm to
the animal and to the public. A sufficient barrier system must be in place to assure the safety of all animals and the public.
Correct by 7 November 2024.

During the first day of the inspection on 16 October 2024, the primary enclosures of 6 alpacas and 27 fallow deer were
flood irrigated, a routine action by the facility to water the landscape and provide cooling measures in hot weather. A
facility representative indicated they have the ability to control how much water is released during flood irrigation of
primary enclosures. Nearly the entirety of the enclosure for the alpacas was covered in standing water approximately 12
inches deep minimum in most parts. There was one dry area of ground with no shade or shelter approximately 14 feet x
14 feet in size that had a smaller cement pad for hay and feedstuff. The animals were observed to walk through and stand
in standing water in order to access shade, shelter, food or drinking water.
Approximately 1/3 of the surface area of the enclosure for the fallow deer was covered in muddy water approximately 6
inches deep in a patchy and marshy pattern. Due to the irregular collection of water on the ground, the animals were
observed to walk through and stand in standing water in order to access shade, shelter, food or drinking water. A majority
of the water soaked into the ground when inspected in the afternoon of the next day, for both enclosures. The attending
veterinarian indicated the facility has not observed hoof issues related to flood irrigation of enclosures in these animals.
Animals that do not have access to dry areas or must wade through water to access resources may experience
discomfort, distress or medical issues related to prolonged contact with standing water. A suitable method shall be
provided to rapidly eliminate excess water. The method of drainage shall comply with applicable Federal, State, and local
laws and regulations relating to pollution control or the protection of the environment.
Correct by 7 November 2024.

At the time of the inspection there are two open tears, each of approximately four inches in diameter, in the rear-side
netting of the enclosure housing one adult vulturine guinea fowl. There are other, larger areas of netting that show
evidence of prior damage repaired with metal clips. Enclosures in need of repairs such as these cannot reliably contain
the birds inside or prevent the entry of birds and other animals from the outside. Birds could escape or become injured or
ill due to entry of outside birds or other animals. A worker was called to make repairs to the open tears when the inspector
called attention to them, and this was corrected during the time of the inspection on 16 October 2024.
Inside the enclosures containing two adult blue and gold macaws and one adult African gray parrot, there are wooden
shelter boxes with peeled paint and many places where the wood is more extensively damaged with broken and/or
delaminating plywood. Surfaces that are damaged in such a manner pose a risk of illness or injury to birds because they
cannot be readily cleaned and sanitized and may have sharp areas.
The facility must ensure that primary enclosures are designed and constructed of suitable materials so that they are
structurally sound and kept in good repair to protect the health of the birds and to contain the birds while restricting the
entry of outside animals; additionally, all surfaces which come into contact with the birds must be maintained so they can
be readily cleaned and/or sanitized or replaced when worn or soiled.
Correct by 30 October 2024.

During inspection, it was noted on disposition records that a Golden Taveta Weaver was missing on 23 September 2024.
Facility representatives confirmed the outdoor housed bird went missing and was never recovered due to unknown cause.
They stated that keepers noticed a snake in the area around the time the bird went missing, but never saw the snake
enter the primary enclosure of the bird. The facility reports they inspected the enclosure and found no defects. The metal
wire enclosure approximately 8 feet wide x 25 feet long x 7 feet tall sits on packed dirt with no dig barrier at the base. Two
areas of erosion at the base of the enclosure were noted by inspectors, approximately 2 inches wide and 4 inches wide
each. Failure to maintain primary enclosures in good repair to securely contain birds may result in their serious injury or
non-recovery in event of escape.
Primary enclosures must be constructed and maintained so that they contain the birds securely.
Correct from this date forward of 24 October 2024.

Approximately 4 Common Ostrich in the African Train Ride enclosure have complete feather loss over the rump region
exposing bare skin that appears unaffected at time of inspection. Facility representatives and the attending veterinarian
acknowledge that birds are plucking feathers from each other and attribute it to normal behavior and seasonal hormonal
change. The avian environment enhancement plan of the facility states that feather plucking in birds due to social factors
will be addressed. No corrective action was taken by the facility per facility representatives due to considering this normal
behavior for female ostrich only herds to display this behavior during breeding season. Failure to address incompatibility
among animals may lead to their discomfort, distress or physical harm. Birds may not be housed with other animals,
including members of their own species, unless they are compatible, do not prevent access to food, water or shelter by
individual animals, and are not known to be hazardous to the health and well-being of each other. Compatibility must be
determined in accordance with generally accepted professional practices and by actual observations to ensure that the
birds are, in fact, compatible.
Correct by 14 November 2024.
This inspection and exit interview were conducted with the facility representatives.
Additional Inspectors:
Tamila Stott, VETERINARY MEDICAL OFFICER n
